    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-12-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-12-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="487"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d487">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/519a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Attorney General</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-12-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 2, 1910</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your telegram of this date in which you state [etc.].</p>
                <p>In reply I have the honor to inform you that the following aide mémoire has been
                    sent to the Mexican embassy to-day: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>The Attorney General is prepared to receive from the Mexican embassy a
                            full statement as to any legal evidence in its possession which would
                            seem to warrant the arrest or detention of Francisco I. Madero and which
                            it may desire to have laid before the competent legal authorities of the
                            United States.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0454" n="372" xml:id="pg_372"/>
                <p>It is unnecessary to add that this being a legal question, it is not one in which
                    this Department feels competent to express itself as to the propriety or
                    sufficiency of the grounds for either the arrest or the detention of Madero.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.],</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
